(1086, 2, '2013-05-20 13:29:55', '2013-05-20 13:29:55', 'LBI is pleased to announce our new, totally redesigned website after a year of developmental work! Upon designing the site, we aimed to make it very “car-centric” in every regard. Many large, high-resolution photos focusing on the beauty, correctness, and originality of the fine examples LBI has on offer. User friendly and intuitive functionality was also a huge focus in design work.  The new site exemplifies our professionalism, wide variety of services offered, and most of all, the unique classic cars that we are proud to present.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nPlease take a moment to browse the brand new site. Contact us if you would like to sell your car, consign it with LBI, or would simply like to talk cars.  Be sure to follow us on <a href="https://www.facebook.com/pages/Luxury-Brokers-International/165561913469224" target="_blank">Facebook</a>, <a href="https://twitter.com/lbilimited" target="_blank">Twitter</a>, and <a href="http://instagram.com/luxurybrokersint" target="_blank">Instagram</a> for new offerings, news about the classic car market, and our road to the next exciting car find. Additionally, we would like to thank website designers, <a href="http://www.pinnacleperformancepartners.com" target="_blank">Pinnacle Performance Partners</a> for a job well done.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;', 'Website Launch!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'website-launch', '', '', '2013-05-20 13:29:55', '2013-05-20 13:29:55', '', 0, 'http://www.pinnacleperformancepartners.co/dev.LBI/?p=124', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1087, 2, '2013-05-03 13:31:34', '2013-05-03 13:31:34', 'The past 6 months have been extremely busy with shows, auctions, and day-to-day activities. In an effort to expand our business, we have opened up a beautiful storage facility. Globe Dye Works, located just outside center city Philadelphia, was built in 1865 as a textile mill that was fully operational up until its closure in 2005. Presently, it has been transformed into a community of artists and unique businesses. We are proud to be a part of the Globe Community where our 8,000 square foot space can house over 30 cars in a climate controlled environment with state-of-the-art security, and a warm atmosphere.  Brick walls, exposed iron beams, solid wood columns, and big factory windows of the early 1900’s were all preserved in an effort to create an atmosphere that complements our beautiful cars of the same era.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nWe are now aggressively pursuing the purchase of quality cars, accepting interesting consignments, and cars for storage. A cocktail party announcement will be made in the coming months.  For more information about our new home in Globe Dye Works, please visit <a href="http://www.globedyeworks.com">www.globedyeworks.com</a> or find them on Facebook.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href="http://pinnacleperformancepartners.co/dev.LBI/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/Globe-Collage.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-2469" alt="Globe Collage" src="http://www.lbilimited.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/Globe-Collage.jpg" width="1936" height="1452" /></a>', 'Announcing the New LBI Facility', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'new-lbi-facility', '', '', '2013-05-03 13:31:34', '2013-05-03 13:31:34', '', 0, 'http://www.pinnacleperformancepartners.co/dev.LBI/?p=125', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1088, 2, '2013-05-08 18:01:49', '2013-05-08 18:01:49', 'Quite often, we are posed with the question; can an automobile be an investment? This simple yet complex question will set the stage for the primary topic of this “Alternative Investments” blog. What constitutes a car as an “investment?” What attributes does any given genre of cars have to qualify it as investment grade? Does originality matter? Does quality of restoration matter? If U.S government officials were to put these questions to paper, this post would be 1000 pages long (and counting), have conflicting views about every “answer”, and they would extend the submission deadline to next year for fear that they would actually have to come up with a conclusion. Rather, I will try to explain this in a much more concise fashion because like the rest of us ordinary folk, we actually need to carry on with our lives.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nIn approximately the last 30 years, classic cars generally from the 20’s through the late 60’s have progressively increased in value enough that if one had the money to shell out for a Series I Jaguar XKE Roadster in the early 2000’s, they would be seeing a healthy return on original purchase price in today’s market. Increases and decreases usually follow the same curve as the stock market. The criterion for an auto investment is not set in stone but for a car to appreciate in value, it typically has the following traits:\n\n&nbsp;\n-Low production numbers\n-Pedigree of the specific marque or model of the car\n-“Coolness factor” of when the specific model was originally produced and available to the public\n-What the cars original intent was\n-Overall appealing look/design in the public eye\n-Positive mile stone model for a specific marque or the advancement of automobile history in general\n\n&nbsp;\n\nOf course, others factors may be included. In order to make a sensible auto investment, one must be very knowledgeable of the specific car in question, vigilant of comparable cars available, and a little insightful (with a little luck involved) as to where the market may go. Condition, price, colors, and production number are all factors that must be considered in investing. Many experts say, “do not buy a car for investment purpose only” which is a bit contradictory because the Wall Street, car-ignorant business man buying a Mercedes 280SL solely as an investment is slim to none. There is always some element of driving enjoyment for the person investing that causes the purchase in the first place.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nLike any other proper portfolio, diversification is always paramount in successful investing. Investing yourself only in gold or a single stock is never a safe way to go; classic cars are no different. It is only a way to diversify a portfolio with a tangible investment. Perhaps with a car that you had in the 60’s when you were carting around your high school sweetheart or drag racing your friends on a Friday night. It is the nostalgic factor mixed with the driving experience, and proud ownership of the car in your garage that are traits of any car investor. Obviously, it takes a certain kind of person for this type of investment.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nThis blog will be address to that type of person providing information on hot new trends in the market, tips on investing in classics, and auction analysis.\nStay tuned for all this and more to come!', 'Automobiles as Investments?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'automobiles-as-investments', '', '', '2013-05-08 18:01:49', '2013-05-08 18:01:49', '', 0, 'http://www.pinnacleperformancepartners.co/dev.LBI/?p=544', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1089, 2, '2013-05-08 18:03:11', '2013-05-08 18:03:11', 'Let’s say you are someone who likes classic cars, always wanted to own one, but needs an excuse to give your spouse when they walk into the garage and see a shiny red Porsche under a not so inconspicuous car cover. Here are a couple cars that have seen slight increases in market value that seem to be good investments for the near future and beyond:\n\n&nbsp;\n\n1. Mercedes-Benz Pagoda’s i.e the famous 280SL, 250SL, and 230SL along with the 190SL. With the recent trend in 300SL Roadster/Gullwing prices hovering around the million dollar mark; this has caused a sort of slinky effect that bumped up prices of the more common Pagoda and 190SL line to trade at higher values than ever before. Folks that may want a Gullwing that cannot afford the hefty price tag that comes with it, will look to its close relatives for similar styling and performance. Right now is a good time to buy and enjoy your Mercedes for the Summer/Fall with the intent of selling within the next year and a half. Why the short term ownership? Because it is the 50th year anniversary since the first 230SL was produces making it a great time to buy/sell while the price frenzy is continuing throughout the year.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n2. Porsche 911’s and 912’s are other hot items on today’s market. It would be a good time to buy or sell seeing as it is the 50th anniversary of the original 911. With 911 “S” prices sky-high primarily due to the Steve McQueen 911 doing over a million dollars about a year and a half ago, prices for SWB, T, E, and L models along with the 912 have seen healthy increases. These are great driver’s cars that exemplify Porsche’s raw, early performance built German engineering that are sure to put a smile on your face.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n50th Anniversary for a particular production model is a common trend here with regard to an upswing in prices. Keep this in mind for the future. Now, when your spouse sees the car under the cover, you confidently proclaim, “It is an investment! Not just a toy!”\n\n&nbsp;\n\nPlease take a look at our <a href="http://www.lbilimited.com/manufacturers/current-offerings/">Current Offerings Page</a> for a beautifully original Porsche 912 and factory Triple Black, U.S Version Mercedes-Benz 280SL.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-2473" alt="280SL Black/Black" src="http://www.lbilimited.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/IMG_39761-e1369065038212.jpg" width="200" height="200" />\n\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-2474" alt="66 912 photo" src="http://www.lbilimited.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/66-912-9-e1369065209540.jpg" width="200" height="133" />\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;', 'Sub $140,000 Smart Buys', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'sub-140000-smart-buys', '', '', '2013-05-08 18:03:11', '2013-05-08 18:03:11', '', 0, 'http://www.pinnacleperformancepartners.co/dev.LBI/?p=546', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(8616, 2, '2013-05-29 13:38:14', '2013-05-29 13:38:14', 'It is starting to feel more and more like summer here on the east coast with the humid, hot weather already upon us. This time of year marks a fun event in the LBI calender; The Greenwich Concours d\' Elegance held this weekend at the Roger Sherman Baldwin Park in Greenwich, Connecticut. The show runs from Saturday June 1st, 10:00am-5:00pm through Sunday, June 2nd with the same hours. Coinciding with the show is the Bonhams Auction that starts at 9:30am on Sunday. The auction is always a great time with Bonhams consigning a bunch of special cars this year including a Pebble Beach winning 1930 Bugatti Type 43. We particularly love lot number 341, an extremely rare 1967 Aston Martin DB6 Vantage Volante. Overall, this will be a fun event for the whole family and we encourage everyone in the tri-state area to attend. We will be there Sunday bright and early!\n\n&nbsp;\n\nSome new arrivals have also graced the LBI facility with their good looks. A striking 1967 Porsche 912 in factory Aga Blue with Red leatherette interior. All matching numbers with recent paint and mechanical servicing but still retains its original interior from 1967! Sitting next to it is a rare and special 1958 Lancia B24 Spider that is in for storage and restoration work that we displayed a quick snapshot on <a href="http://instagram.com/luxurybrokersint#">our Instagram</a> . Also new is a spectacularly running 1958 Jaguar XK-150 FHC in Cotswald Blue over Red with many photos and a short video of us test driving it on <a href="http://www.youtube.com/user/LuxuryBrokersInt">our YouTube page</a>. Do you like American power plants? Just in is a 1974 DeTomaso Pantera GTS and 1965 Shelby Cobra CSX Continuation car that can both be seen on our <a href="http://www.lbilimited.com/manufacturers/current-offerings/">Current Offerings</a> section.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nFor more information on the Greenwich Concours, please visit the show\'s site <a href="http://www.greenwichconcours.com/Main.htm">here</a>. Stay up to date by following us on our social media outlets and check the website frequently for new additions and announcements from the LBI crew!', 'Greenwich Concours and New Arrivals', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'greenwich-concours-and-new-arrivals', '', '', '2013-05-29 13:38:14', '2013-05-29 13:38:14', '', 0, 'http://www.lbilimited.com/?p=8616', 0, 'post', '', 0);

